        "#### Define the Statistical Model¥n",
        "¥n",
        "Define the statistical model (E, P_theta-in-Theta) associated with this experiment involving censored data, clearly defining the sample space, family of probability measures, and parameter space.¥n",
        "¥n",
        "¥n",
        "**Define the sample space, $E$, for the observed data.**¥n",
        "- Given $n$ independent observations $Y_1, ¥¥dots, Y_n$, where each $Y_i$ can take values in ${0, 1}$, the sample space $E$ is the set of all possible outcomes for the entire sample. This can be represented as $ E = ¥¥{ (y_1, ¥¥dots, y_n) : y_i ¥¥in ¥¥{0, 1¥¥} ¥¥text{ for all } i = 1, ¥¥dots, n ¥¥} = ¥¥{0, 1¥¥}^n $¥n",
        "¥n",
        "**Define the parameter space, $¥¥Theta$, for the parameter $¥¥theta$.**¥n",
        "- It was established that for the rate parameter $¥¥lambda = -¥¥ln ¥¥theta$ to be positive and thus a valid exponential distribution, the parameter $¥¥theta$ must be in the range $(0, 1)$. Therefore, the parameter space $¥¥Theta$ is: $ ¥¥Theta = (0, 1)$. This means that $¥¥theta$ is a real number such that $0 < ¥¥theta < 1$.¥n",
        "¥n",
        "¥n",
        "**Define the family of probability measures, $P_{¥¥theta ¥¥in ¥¥Theta}$**.¥n",
        "- Each $Y_i$ follows a Bernoulli distribution, where $P(Y_i=1) = ¥¥theta^¥¥tau$. Thus, the pmf for a single observation $Y_i$ is given by $P(Y_i = y_i; ¥¥theta, ¥¥tau) = (¥¥theta^¥¥tau)^{y_i} (1 - ¥¥theta^¥¥tau)^{1 - y_i} ¥¥text{ for } y_i ¥¥in ¥¥{0, 1¥¥}$. Where $¥¥tau$ is a known constant related to the censoring time. The parameter $¥¥theta$ is the one we are interested in.¥n",
        "¥n",
        "¥n",
        "**The joint probability mass function, pmf**¥n",
        "- Use the independence of the $Y_i$ observations for the joint probability mass function, pmf of the entire sample $Y_1, ¥¥dots, Y_n$.¥n",
        "- Given that the observations $Y_1, ¥¥dots, Y_n$ are independent and i.i.d., the joint PMF for the entire sample is the product of the individual PMFs $P(Y_1=y_1, ¥¥dots, Y_n=y_n; ¥¥theta, ¥¥tau) = ¥¥prod_{i=1}^n P(Y_i=y_i; ¥¥theta, ¥¥tau)$¥n",
        "- Substituting the PMF for a single observation $P(y_1, ¥¥dots, y_n; ¥¥theta, ¥¥tau) = ¥¥prod_{i=1}^n (¥¥theta^¥¥tau)^{y_i} (1 - ¥¥theta^¥¥tau)^{1 - y_i}$¥n",
        "- This can be rewritten by separating the terms $P(y_1, ¥¥dots, y_n; ¥¥theta, ¥¥tau) = (¥¥theta^¥¥tau)^{¥¥sum_{i=1}^n y_i} (1 - ¥¥theta^¥¥tau)^{n - ¥¥sum_{i=1}^n y_i}$¥n",
        "- Let $S = ¥¥sum_{i=1}^n y_i$ be the sum of the observations (number of 'successes' or uncensored observations). Then the joint PMF is $P(y_1, ¥¥dots, y_n; ¥¥theta, ¥¥tau) = (¥¥theta^¥¥tau)^{S} (1 - ¥¥theta^¥¥tau)^{n - S}$"
      ]
