        "#### MLE for Censored Data¥n",
        "¥n",
        "MLE for theta based on the censored data Y1,...,Yn.¥n",
        "¥n",
        "**The likelihood function**¥n",
        "- $Y_i$ follows a Bernoulli distribution with parameter $p = ¥¥theta^¥¥tau$, where $¥¥tau = ¥¥frac{T_{cens}}{E[X]}$. The pmf for a single Bernoulli trial $Y_i$ is $P(Y_i=y_i) = p^{y_i} (1-p)^{1-y_i} = (¥¥theta^¥¥tau)^{y_i} (1-¥¥theta^¥¥tau)^{1-y_i}$. For $n$ i.i.d. observations $Y_1, ¥¥dots, Y_n$, the likelihood function $L(¥¥theta)$ is the product of their individual pmfs $ L(¥¥theta) = ¥¥prod_{i=1}^n (¥¥theta^¥¥tau)^{y_i} (1-¥¥theta^¥¥tau)^{1-y_i}$. Let $S = ¥¥sum_{i=1}^n y_i$ be the number of ¥"successes¥" (i.e., observations where $Y_i=1$) and $n-S = ¥¥sum_{i=1}^n (1-y_i)$ be the number of ¥"failures¥" (i.e., observations where $Y_i=0$).¥n",
        "¥n",
        "The likelihood function is $ L(¥¥theta) = (¥¥theta^¥¥tau)^S (1-¥¥theta^¥¥tau)^{n-S} $$¥n",
        "¥n",
        "**The log-likelihood function**¥n",
        "- $l(¥¥theta) = ¥¥ln¥¥left( (¥¥theta^¥¥tau)^S (1-¥¥theta^¥¥tau)^{n-S} ¥¥right)$, $¥¥quad$ $ l(¥¥theta) = ¥¥ln((¥¥theta^¥¥tau)^S) + ¥¥ln((1-¥¥theta^¥¥tau)^{n-S})$, $¥¥quad$ $ l(¥¥theta) = S ¥¥ln(¥¥theta^¥¥tau) + (n-S) ¥¥ln(1-¥¥theta^¥¥tau)$¥n",
        "¥n",
        "Further simplifying the first term $l(¥¥theta) = S ¥¥tau ¥¥ln(¥¥theta) + (n-S) ¥¥ln(1-¥¥theta^¥¥tau)$¥n",
        "¥n",
        "**Differentiate the log-likelihood**, $l(¥¥theta)$, with respect to $¥¥theta$. Be careful with the chain rule when differentiating terms involving $¥¥theta^¥¥tau$.¥n",
        "- Given the log-likelihood function $l(¥¥theta) = S ¥¥tau ¥¥ln(¥¥theta) + (n-S) ¥¥ln(1-¥¥theta^¥¥tau)$, we differentiate $l(¥¥theta)$ with respect to $¥¥theta$ $ ¥¥frac{dl}{d¥¥theta} = ¥¥frac{d}{d¥¥theta} [S ¥¥tau ¥¥ln(¥¥theta)] + ¥¥frac{d}{d¥¥theta} [(n-S) ¥¥ln(1-¥¥theta^¥¥tau)]$.¥n",
        "¥n",
        "The derivative of the log-likelihood is $ ¥¥frac{dl}{d¥¥theta} = ¥¥frac{S ¥¥tau}{¥¥theta} - ¥¥frac{(n-S) ¥¥tau ¥¥theta^{¥¥tau-1}}{1-¥¥theta^¥¥tau}$¥n",
        "¥n",
        "**Set the derivative $¥¥frac{dl}{d¥¥theta}$ equal to zero and solve for $¥¥theta$**. This gives the MLE, $¥¥hat{¥¥theta}$. We solve for $¥¥theta$, $¥¥hat{¥¥theta} = ¥¥left(¥¥frac{S}{n}¥¥right)^{1/¥¥tau}$¥n",
        "¥n",
        "**Express the MLE, $¥¥hat{¥¥theta}$, in terms of the number of 'successes' ($S = ¥¥sum_{i=1}^n Y_i$) and the total number of observations ($n$).**¥n",
        "¥n",
        "We found the MLE to be $¥¥hat{¥¥theta} = ¥¥left(¥¥frac{S}{n}¥¥right)^{1/¥¥tau}$, where:¥n",
        "- $S = ¥¥sum_{i=1}^n Y_i$ is the number of 'successes' (observed events before censoring time $T_{cens}$). In the context of censored data, $Y_i=1$ if $X_i ¥¥le T_{cens}$ and $Y_i=0$ if $X_i > T_{cens}$.¥n",
        "- $n$ is the total number of observations.¥n",
        "- $¥¥tau = ¥¥frac{T_{cens}}{E[X]}$ is a constant defined in earlier steps, representing the ratio of the censoring time to the expectation of $X_i$ (which itself depends on the unknown parameter $¥¥theta$). However, for the purpose of deriving the MLE for $p = ¥¥theta^¥¥tau$, $¥¥tau$ is treated as a known constant.¥n",
        "¥n",
        "This expression clearly states the MLE $¥¥hat{¥¥theta}$ in terms of the observed sample statistics ($S$ and $n$) and the given constant $¥¥tau$ related to the censoring time.¥n"
