        "#### General Conditions for MLE Consistency¥n",
        "¥n",
        "Maximum Likelihood Estimators (MLEs) are generally consistent under certain regularity conditions. These conditions ensure that as the sample size $n$ approaches infinity, the MLE converges in probability to the true parameter value.¥n",
        "¥n",
        "The key regularity conditions typically include:¥n",
        "¥n",
        "1.  **Identically and Independently Distributed (i.i.d.) Data**: The observations $X_1, ¥¥dots, X_n$ are i.i.d. random variables.¥n",
        "2.  **Model Specification**: The probability distribution of the data is correctly specified (i.e., the true parameter $¥¥theta_0$ belongs to the parameter space $¥¥Theta$).¥n",
        "3.  **Identifiability**: Different parameter values lead to different probability distributions (i.e., if $¥¥theta_1 ¥¥ne ¥¥theta_2$, then $f(x; ¥¥theta_1) ¥¥ne f(x; ¥¥theta_2)$ for some $x$).¥n",
        "4.  **Continuity and Differentiability**: The log-likelihood function $l(¥¥theta; x)$ is at least twice continuously differentiable with respect to $¥¥theta$.¥n",
        "5.  **Finite Fisher Information**: The Fisher Information $I(¥¥theta)$ is finite and positive for all $¥¥theta ¥¥in ¥¥Theta$.¥n",
        "6.  **Domination**: The support of the probability density function (PDF) does not depend on the parameter $¥¥theta$, or there exist integrable functions that bound the derivatives of the log-likelihood function.¥n",
        "¥n",
        "Under these regularity conditions, the MLE $¥¥hat{¥¥theta}_n$ is consistent, meaning it converges in probability to the true parameter $¥¥theta_0$ as $n ¥¥to ¥¥infty$¥n",
        "- $¥¥hat{¥¥theta}_n ¥¥xrightarrow{P} ¥¥theta_0$"
      ]
